    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with hypertension</h2>
      <p>Hypertension in cats causes ongoing damage to the kidneys, eyes, brain, and heart — often before any outward signs appear. The damage is cumulative and can be severe before it becomes visible. This is what makes it particularly important to monitor in cats with CKD or hyperthyroidism, where blood pressure elevation is common and expected.</p>
      <p>Yams had hypertension alongside his CKD. Sorbet is currently managed for it as part of his multi-condition picture. In both cases, the hypertension diagnosis came through asking for a blood pressure check — not because something obvious prompted it. That pattern is common. Blood pressure is not always measured as a routine part of CKD or hyperthyroidism appointments, even though it should be.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>A hypertensive crisis can cause sudden blindness.</strong> If your cat suddenly seems unable to see — bumping into things, dilated and unresponsive pupils — this is an emergency. Go to a vet immediately. Caught early, some vision loss can be reversed.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask for blood pressure to be checked at every appointment if your cat has CKD, hyperthyroidism, or heart disease.</strong> These conditions are strongly associated with hypertension. It is not always measured automatically — ask for it.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask for the actual reading, not just "okay" or "a bit high."</strong> Blood pressure in cats can be affected by stress at the vet, so a single reading needs context. Ask what the number was, and whether it warrants a repeat measurement.</li>
        <li><strong>If treatment is started, ask what target you're working toward and how you'll know it's being achieved.</strong> Blood pressure management is ongoing, and the goal should be specific — not just "lower."</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about urine protein alongside blood pressure.</strong> Elevated blood pressure causes protein to appear in the urine, which itself damages the kidneys further. Some medications address both. Ask whether urine protein has been assessed.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

